Update to Santa Cruz County Eviction Moratorium & Workshop for Renters and Landlords

What: Zoom Workshop (meeting) for both tenants and landlords. On Tuesday, August 18, the Santa Cruz County Board of Supervisors extended the moratorium on evictions to Sept. 30 and approved $1.1 million in CARES funding for an Emergency Rental Assistance Program (ERAP) to be administered by the Community Action Board (CAB) and Families In Transition (FIT) . Applications are due Sept. 15th.

When: September 3rd, 7:00 pm - 8:30 pm

Registration Link: https://forms.gle/AXkA3vTYFaVwYkxv6

Who: Both tenants and landlords living/owning in unincorporated county communities of Live Oak, Soquel, Aptos, Freedom, Santa Cruz Mountains, etc. will qualify for this grant but others are encouraged to connect to the meeting and learn about other possible resources.

post_text:
Tips for Parents for Online Learning:
One of the most important tips for online learning is communication with your student!

Begin and end the day by checking-in

In the morning, you might ask:

• What classes/subject do you have today?
• Do you have any assessments?
• How will you spend your time?
• What resources do you need?
• What can I do to help?

At the end of the day you might ask:

• How far did you get in your learning tasks today?
• What did you discover? What was hard?
• What could we do to make tomorrow better?

Checking in students to process instructions they received from their teachers helps them to organize themselves and set priorities – older students too. Not all students thrive in distance learning; some struggle with too much independence or lack of structure. These check-in routines can help avoid later challenges and disappointments. They help students develop self-management and executive functioning that are essential skills for life. Parents are good life coaches.

from: www.acs-schools.com/parents-guide-distance-learning

Tip Tuesday! Since the Job market appears to be opening up, we are switching back to job tips. The difference is is that we will focus on tip for finding a job during COVID-19.

Here are a great article from George Williams College on 12 Tips to navigate your job search during COVID-19
https://gwc.aurora.edu/news/archive/12-tips-to-navigate-your-job-search-during-covid-19.html

The best tips from this article are:
1. Keep your online profile updated.
2. Tailor your cover letter and resume to the specific job your are applying for - can not stress this one enough!!!
3. Practice a virtual or phone interview before one actually happens.

#wegotthis #jobsduringcovid19 #jobseeker #jobs #tiptuesday #lovesccs #santacruzcityschools #santacruz

With School almost out, we would like to share with our community the following information regarding free meals:

Its Tip Tuesday for Parents! With school ending, we all need ideas to entertain or teach our children during the summer.

Here is a link to GoPeer which is a website were Harvard, MIT, Stanford Students Volunteer to Tutor K-12 Students for Free: https://medium.com/gopeer/harvard-mit-stanford-students-volunteer-to-tutor-k-12-students-for-free-2a29177d0080

Also, if you and your children are done with school and looking for something different, inexpensive and fun to do, here is a link to Today's Parent's 87 Family activities to help you avoid cabin fever: https://www.todaysparent.com/family/activities/fun-things-to-do-at-home/

#wegotthis #lovesccs #santacruz #santacruzcityschools #tiptuesdayforparents

shared_text:
Delaveaga Dragons
May 26 at 3:00 PM ·

Through generous donations, we are able to give a yearbook to every DeLaveaga student this year! A group of volunteers will be handing out yearbooks in front of DeLaveaga on the following days/times:

Wednesday, May 27th from 2-5pm

Thursday, May 28th from 9am-12 noon

Please drive around the parking lot as you would if you were dropping or picking up your child and STAY in your cars! Volunteers will bring the yearbooks to your cars while wearing masks and gloves.

If you are unable to pick-up your yearbooks this week, you will be able to get a yearbook next Fall.

Any questions please email delayearbook@gmail.com

post_text:
Some Memorial Day History to share with the kiddos!

Memorial Day is a federal holiday in the United States observed every last Monday in May. Initially, it meant to commemorate fallen soldiers during the Civil War. In the 1900s, it became a celebration to honor soldiers who died in any war while serving the country and was formerly known as Decoration Day.

https://kidskonnect.com/holidays-seasons/memorial-day/

post_text:
Guelaguetza Online! - Sunday May 17, 2020
Sunday May 17 would have been the 15th anniversary of our Vive Oaxaca Guelaguetza festival in Santa Cruz, but, sadly, we cannot be together this year. We are happy to share videos so you can feel the Guelaguetza spirit of giving while you stay safely at home. Guelaguetza is an indigenous Zapotec word meaning a commitment of sharing and a spirit of cooperation - something we especially need during this time.

https://mailchi.mp/27edaac056b5/join-us-for-virtual-guelaguetza-may-17?e=9ca73b44f8
Senderos #distancelearning #guelaguetza #santacruz

Delaveaga Dragons
April 28 at 5:28 PM ·

Deadline to sponsor a scrolling banner ad on our online auction site is this Friday, May 1st.

-Each ad has the following dimensions: width 231px, height 95px
-Choose any design you like (your logo and/or advertise specific promotion)
-All ads can redirect to your preferred website
-The auction site will be live for at least 7 days.
-Each ad is $100
-Deadline to submit payment and ad media requirements is May 1st.

Click on the link below for a sneak peak of our auction and to see placement of scrolling banner ads.

Auction Link https://bit.ly/2YbXNHz

The DeLaveaga PTC is excited to announce that we are partnering with the Branciforte Middle School Home & School Club this year to put on our annual online auction.

We will have over 140 items (more to be added) to bid on including 5 sets of 4-tickets to Disneyland. The date of the online auction will be announced soon! Date currently listed on auction site is not final.

Scotts Valley Police Department
April 24 at 3:39 PM ·

FACEMASKS REQUIRED IN PUBLIC STARTING TONIGHT:

The Santa Cruz County Health Officer has issued a new order requiring all residents older than twelve years old to wear a face covering when out in public conducting essential activities, including the use of public transit. The Order goes into effect at midnight tonight and intends to slow the spread of COVID-19.

Community members must wear a face covering while inside or waiting in line to enter an essential business, facility, or location. Businesses have the right to deny service to anyone not wearing a face covering. All essential businesses must require their employees and volunteers to wear a face covering.

A face covering is NOT required when exercising outdoors but it’s recommended you carry one in case you are unable to social distance yourself from others. Children under two must NOT wear them due to the risk of suffocation.

https://www.santacruzhealth.org/Portals/7/Pdfs/Coronavirus/PHO%20Order%20Face%20Coverings%20April%2024.pdf?version=042320

Delaveaga Dragons
April 22 at 9:14 PM ·

-SPONSORSHIP OPPORTUNITIES-
The DeLaveaga PTC is excited to announce that we are partnering with the Branciforte Middle School Home School Club this year to put out our annual online auction.

We will have over 100 items to bid on including 5 sets of 4-tickets to Disneyland. The date of the online auction will be announced soon!

In the mean time, we're looking for sponsors for our scrolling banner ads that are visible on every page of the auction site.

-Each ad has the following dimensions: width 231px, height 95px
-The ad can be your company logo or advertise a specific promotion
-All ads can redirect to your preferred website
-The auction site will be live for at least 7 days.
-Each ad is $100
-Below is a screenshot of the placement of banner ads (last year)
-Deadline to submit payment and ad media requirements is May 1st.

Send us a Direct Message for more info!

post_text:
Congratulations to @BranciforteSmallSchools AFE student Phoenix who won Third Place in the @SantaCruzCaliforniaScienceFair!

He was also going to be sent to the California State Science Fair. Since it was canceled, he relayed that they are just sending him an award, but he does not know what it is yet. In addition, he was selected as an alternate for the International Science Fair, but that is most likely canceled too.

Due to the Coronavirus, Santa Cruz California Science Fair participants were judged by sending in photos and a video of their project, and talked to judges by phone.

Phoenix’s written overview of his Science project “Algae Takes Flight”:

For his project he swabbed different Seabirds and waterfowl to identify whether or not the each species in his experiment could carry algae in its’ feathers.

#santacruzcaliforniasciencefair #brancifortesmallschools #Algartakesflight #lovesccs #santacruz #santacruzcityschools

post_text:
This #TipTuesday is for those of us that are required to WorkfromHome. There are #10tips that seem very helpful. These tips could also apply to homeschooling children.

1. Maintain regular hours
2. Create a morning routine
3. Schedule breaks
4. Take breaks in their entirety
5. Don’t hesitate to ask for what you need to get your work done (have your child ask for help if needed)
6. Show up to meetings and be heard (Virtually speaking of course)
7. Take Sick days if needed (this applies to you or your child)
8. Be positive! (this will help your child as well!)
9. Don’t be too hard on yourself (or your child)
10. End your day with a routine (end your child's day with a routine)

#santacruzcityschools #lovesccs #workfromhome
Some of the tips come from this website:
https://www.pcmag.com/news/get-organized-20-tips-for-working-from-home

Our #WholeSchoolApproach to #RestorativeJustice:
Restorative Justice in schools is a set of principles and practices that build community and involve processes that restore relationships when harm has occurred. Our schools are using Restorative Practices with the understanding that building relationships and community help us when confronted with wrongdoing. Several of our district schools have participated in training with #SEEDS a non-profit that supports school communities in implementing restorative practices.
https://www.seedscrc.org/rj-schools
#seeds #restorativejustice SEEDS #lovesccs #santacruz

post_text:
Welcome Transitional Kindergartners and Kindergartners!
Our Secondary Open Enrollment window is open! We are currently accepting applications for Interdistrict (students from another district who want to attend SCCS) and Intradistrict transfers (students in our district who want to attend a different SCCS site).
The window for Transitional Kindergarten and Kindergarten Enrollment for the 2020-21 School Year opened February 18, 2020. To be eligible for Transitional Kindergarten, students must be turning 5 years old between September 2 through December 2. To be eligible for Kindergarten enrollment, students must be 5 years old on or before September 1 of the year in which the student enters Kindergarten.
#kindergartners #lovesccs #santacruz
text:
Welcome Transitional Kindergartners and Kindergartners!
Our Secondary Open Enrollment window is open! We are currently accepting applications for Interdistrict (students from another district who want to attend SCCS) and Intradistrict transfers (students in our district who want to attend a different SCCS site).
The window for Transitional Kindergarten and Kindergarten Enrollment for the 2020-21 School Year opened February 18, 2020. To be eligible for Transitional Kindergarten, students must be turning 5 years old between September 2 through December 2. To be eligible for Kindergarten enrollment, students must be 5 years old on or before September 1 of the year in which the student enters Kindergarten.
#kindergartners #lovesccs #santacruz

post_text:
Show and Contest at the #AptosPublicLibrary:
The theme of the show was to create a book cover, poetry, or ceramic sculptures, for a recently published book entitled #PatriotNumberOne by @LaurenHilgers
* #AptosHigh submitted 20 book covers
* #SoquelHigh submitted 10 book covers

The judge for the book cover contest was a #graphicdesigner from the community with over 25 years of experience.
All of the students received a certificate of participation from the #AptosPublicLibrary.
Soquel High's Lucca Low, took first place for his book cover design and received a certificate, a blue ribbon, and a gift certificate to the Sockshop and Shoe Company! Congratulations Lucca! Great Job!

Stories from Branciforte Small Schools: This year one of Alternative Family Education’s Site Plan goals is to increase families’ and staff’s understanding of the Next Generation Science Standards. To support this learning, teacher leaders offer eight ‘Family Science Nights’, each with a different lens with which to explore the components of the Next Generation Science Standards: the Disciplinary Core Ideas, the Cross Cutting Concepts and the Science and Engineering Practices. The photos are from Science Night 2: Water.

post_text:
Costanoa Gratitude Luncheon:
Every year at Costanoa High School, the teachers organize and prepare a Thanksgiving meal for roughly 100 people. Those invited include Costanoa students, SCCS Maintenance, Grounds and Operations staff and BSSC teachers and support staff. It is a very positive event where those invited write what they are grateful for on paper leaves that they then post on a large paper tree. This year we were fortunate to have Luis Sanchez do an improv dance performance. Luis works regularly with our students and teacher Sharon Mullowney through a SPECTRA Santa Cruz Arts Council grant.
#Costanoa #BSS #Lovesccs #Santacruzcityschools #santacruz #gratitude #thankful

post_text:
District Newsletter Explore Program Nov 8, 2019:
In collaboration with the Santa Cruz Education Foundation (SCEF), Kids EXPLORE After School is continuing to offer fun and engaging after school classes. This Fall we were able to offer after school enrichment at all 5 elementary school sites! We are proud to have served over 600 students last year, offering classes including Art, Language, STEM, Sports, Theater and more.
As the fall session comes to an end, we are already looking forward to the Spring!
● The EXPLORE 2020 Spring Session will begin the week of March 2nd
● Save the Date for our “Kids EXPLORE After School Showcase” on April 1st, 2020.

We are also excited to announce that the Santa Cruz Education Foundation has received the George Ow Jr. Challenge Grant to support the EXPLORE program in providing more affordable classes and scholarships to students in need.

For more information or to learn how you can donate to Kids EXPLORE After School Enrichment, click here or contact Kaley Roth, EXPLORE Program Manager, at
kroth@sccs.net.

La Pitilla Classroom in Nicaragua
This coming spring, One Dollar for Like (ODFL) will build its 15th classroom in Nicaragua at La Pitilla in the state of Tipitapa. The existing classroom is a lean-to shed with a tin roof. If has 30 preschool and elementary students.

Six California high schools are joining together to fund the new classroom:
- Harbor High School
- Santa Cruz High School
- Soquel High School
- Katella High School
- Magnolia High School
- Gahr High School
#onedollarforlife #ODFL #santacruzcityschools #lovesccs

In an effort to reach adult learner and immigrant populations, Cabrillo and GOAL (Greater Opportunities Through Adult Learning) are coordinating an Adult Registration Fair with a focus on our community. This Registration Fair is taking place Friday, December 6th : 3pm-7pm at the Cabrillo Watsonville Center.

Prospective students will be able to register for classes focused on job training/CTE, GED, citizenship, ESL and more. Many classes are free or very low cost and are provided by Cabrillo College, Career Advancement Charter, and Watsonville Aptos Santa Cruz Adult Schools. Please note that NonCredit courses at Cabrillo do not require residency.

post_text:
Tip Tuesday! Make your Resume and Letter of Introduction match the job you are applying for!

We see this all the time, people are looking for a job so they are applying for many different positions at many different locations...

Take the time to research the job you are applying for before you apply! Ask yourself these questions:

1. Does my resume highlight my experience and skills as it pertains to THIS position?

2. Does my Letter of Introduction show that I have done the research for this position?

Tip Tuesday!!!
Even if you’re looking at jobs that are all within the same industry that you are currently working in, it’s still important to tailor your resume so that it matches each specific job you apply to. By doing so, you give yourself a competitive edge over the resumes that hiring managers know are used for any and every job. This is very true with school districts!!!

post_text:
Where we Live Wednesday - Santa Cruz Museum of Art & History (The MAH)
Back in the mid-1980’s, the Santa Cruz Historical Society (founded in 1954) and the Art Museum of Santa Cruz County (founded in 1981) joined forces to build a museum of art and history on the site of the former county jail. The new project—the McPherson Center for Art and History–was sparked by a generous donation from the McPherson family. As Bruce McPherson put it, the dream was to transform the former jail from ”a place of incarceration to a place of inspiration.”
Information from: https://santacruzmah.org/history
#wherewelivewednesday #lovesccs #santacruzcityschools #santacruz
